\par The church was cold. It was October, too early for the heating to be on. Outside, the sun gave a watery promise of warmth and good cheer, but here within the chill grey stone there was only dampness and a sure foreknowledge of winter.
\par Laura stood between Nannie, resplendent in crackling collars and cuffs, and Mr. Henson, the curate. The vicar was in bed with mild influenza. Mr. Henson was young and thin, with an Adam}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s apple and a high nasal voice.
\par Mrs. Franklin, looking frail and attractive, leant on her husband}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s arm. He himself stood upright and grave. The birth of hi
s second daughter had not consoled him for the loss of Charles. He had wanted a son. And it seemed now, from what the doctor had said, that there would not be a son. . . .
\par His eyes went from Laura to the infant in Nannie\rquote s arms gurgling happily to itself.
\par Two daughters . . . Of course Laura was a nice child, a dear child and, as babies go, the new arrival was a splendid specimen, but a man wanted a son.
\par Charles\emdash Charles, with his fair hair, his way of throwing back his head and laughing. Such an attractive boy, so handsome, so bright, so intelligent. Really a very unusual boy. It seemed a pity that if one of his children had to die, it hadn}{
\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 t been Laura. . . .
\par His eyes suddenly met those of his elder daughter, eyes that seemed large and tragic in her small pale face, and Franklin flushed guiltily\emdash 
what had he been thinking of? Suppose the child should guess what had been in his mind. Of course he was devoted to Laura\emdash only\emdash only, she wasn}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
t, she could never be Charles.
\par Leaning against her husband, her eyes half closed, Angela Franklin was saying to herself:
\par }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 My boy\emdash my beautiful boy\emdash my darling. . . . I still can}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 t believe it. Why couldn}{
\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 t it have been Laura?}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
\par She felt no guilt in that thought as it came to her. More ruthless and more honest than her husband, closer
 to primeval needs, she admitted the simple fact that her second child, a daughter, had never meant, and could never mean to her what her first-born had. Compared with Charles, Laura was an anti-climax}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 a quiet disappointing child, well-behaved, giving no trouble, but lacking in}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 what was it?}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 personality.
\par She thought again: }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 Charles}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 nothing can ever make up to me for losing Charles.}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
\par She felt the pressure of her husband}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s hand on her arm, and opened her eyes}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
she must pay attention to the Service. What a very irritating voice poor Mr. Henson had!
\par 
\par 
\par Angela looked with half-amused indulgence at the baby in Nannie}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s arms}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
such big solemn words for such a tiny mite.
\par The baby, who had been sleeping, blinked and opened her eyes. Such dazzling blue eyes}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 like Charles}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s eyes}{
\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 she made a happy gurgling noise.
\par Angela thought: }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 Charles}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s smile.}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970  A rush of mother love swept over her. Her baby}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 her own lovely baby. For the first time Charles}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s death receded into the past.
\par Angela met Laura}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 s dark sad gaze, and thought with momentary curiosity: }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
I wonder just what that child is thinking?}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
\par Nannie also was conscious of Laura standing quiet and erect beside her.
\par }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 Such a quiet little thing,}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970  she thought. }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 A bit too quiet for my taste}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 not natural for any child to be as quiet and well-be
haved as she is. There has never been much notice taken of her}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 maybe not as much as there ought to have been\emdash I wonder now\emdash \rquote 
\par The Reverend Eustace Henson was approaching the moment that always made him nervous. He had not done many christenings. If only the vicar were here. He noticed with approval Laura}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
s grave eyes and serious expression. A well-behaved child. He wondered suddenly what was passing through her mind.
\par It was as well that neither he, nor Nannie, nor Arthur and Angela Franklin knew.
\par It wasn}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 t fair. . . .
\par Oh, it wasn}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 t fair. . . .
\par Her mother loved this baby sister as much as she loved Charles.
\par It wasn}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 t fair. . . .
\par She hated the baby\emdash she hated it, hated it, hated it!
\par }{\i\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 \lquote I\rquote d like her to die.\rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
\par Standing by the font, the solemn words of baptism were ringing in her ears}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 but far more clear, far more real}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 was the thought translated into words:
\par \lquote I\rquote d like her to die. . . .\rquote 
\par There was a gentle nudge. Nannie was handing her the baby, whispering:
\par }{\insrsid5328970 \'93}{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 Careful, now, take her}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 steady}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
and then you hand her to the clergyman.}{\insrsid5328970 \'94}{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970  Laura whispered back: }{\insrsid5328970 \'93}{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 I know.}{\insrsid5328970 \'94}{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
\par Baby was in her arms. Laura looked down at her. She thought: }{\insrsid5328970 \lquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 Supposing I opened my arms and just let her fall}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 on to the stones. Would it kill her?}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
\par Down on to the stones, so hard and grey\emdash but then babies were so well wrapped up, so\emdash }{\i\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 so padded}{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 . Should she? Dare she?
\par She hesitated and then the moment was gone}{\insrsid5328970 \emdash }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 the baby was now in the somewhat nervous arms of the Reverend Eustace Henson, who lacked the practised ease 
of the vicar. He was asking the names and repeating them after Laura Shirley, Margaret, Evelyn. . . . The water trickled off the baby}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
s forehead. She did not cry, only gurgled as though an even more delightful thing than usual had happened to her. Gingerly, with inward shrinking, the curate kissed the baby}{\insrsid5328970 \rquote }{\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5328970 
s forehead. The vicar always did that, he knew. With relief he handed the baby back to Nannie.
\par The christening was over.
